{"title_page": "John of Patmos", "text_new": "{{short description|Christian saint and author of the Book of Revelation}}\n{{Redirect2|John the Divine|John the Revelator|other uses of John the Divine|John the Divine (disambiguation)|other uses of John the Revelator|John the Revelator (disambiguation)|other people called Saint John|Saint John (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox saint\n|name=John of Patmos\n|birth_date=6 AD\n|death_date=~100 AD\n|feast_day=\n|venerated_in= [[Catholic Church]]<br/>[[Eastern Orthodox Church]] \n|image=File:Antonio Palomino 003.JPG\n|imagesize=250px\n|caption=''Saint John the Evangelist on Patmos'' by [[Antonio Palomino]], 17th century\n|death_place=[[Ephesus]], [[Roman Empire]] (?)\n|birth_place= [[Pool of Bethesda]], [[Jerusalem]]\n|beatified_date=\n|beatified_place=\n|beatified_by=\n|canonized_date=\n|major_works=[[Book of Revelation]]\n|canonized_by=\n|attributes=\n|patronage=\n|major_shrine=\n|suppressed_date=\n|issues=\n|prayer=\n|prayer_attrib=\n}}\n{{John}}\n'''John of Patmos''' (also called '''John the Revelator''', '''John the Divine''', '''John the Theologian''', and possibly [[John the Apostle]]; [[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: \u1f38\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u1f41 \u0398\u03b5\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2; {{lang-cop|\u2c93\u2cb1\u2c81\u2c9b\u2c9b\u2c8f\u2ca5}}) could be the author named as John in the [[Book of Revelation]], the [[Apocalyptic literature|apocalyptic]] text forming the final book of the [[New Testament]]. The text of Revelation states that John was on [[Patmos]], a [[Greece|Greek]] island where, by most biblical historians, he is considered to be exiled as a result of anti-Christian persecution under the Roman emperor [[Domitian]].<ref>Souvay, Charles. [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11547a.htm \"Patmos.\"] ''The Catholic Encyclopedia.'' Vol. 11. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 12 Jan. 2009</ref><ref>Phillips, J. B. {{cite web |url=http://www.ccel.org/bible/phillips/CPn27Revelation.htm |title= Book 27 - Book of Revelation |author= |date=12 January 1962 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=}} ''People, Places, Customs, Concepts, Journeys - the New Testament with integrated notes and maps 1962.</ref> \n\nSince the Roman era, Christians and historians have considered the Book of Revelation's writer to be the Apostle John ([[John the Evangelist]]), author of the [[Gospel of John]]. However, a minority of senior clerics and scholars, such as [[Eusebius]] (d. 339/340), recognize at least one further John as a companion of Jesus Christ, [[John the Presbyter]] \"after an interval, placing him among others outside of the number of the apostles\". Some Christian scholars since medieval times separate the disciple(s) from Revelation's writer, John of Patmos/the Divine.<ref name=Harris>Stephen L Harris, ''Understanding the Bible,'' (Palo Alto: Mayfield, 1985), 355</ref><ref name=Ehrman>{{Cite book|last=Ehrman |first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |title=The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings |year=2004 |publisher=Oxford |location=New York |isbn=0-19-515462-2 |page=468 }}</ref>\n\n== Book of Revelation ==\nThe author of the [[Book of Revelation]] identifies himself only as \"John\".<ref name=\"ODCC Revelation, Book of\">\"Revelation, Book of.\" Cross, F. L., ed. The Oxford dictionary of the Christian church. New York: Oxford University Press. 2005</ref> Traditionally, this was often believed to be the same person as [[John the Apostle|John, son of Zebedee]], one of the apostles of Jesus, to whom the [[Gospel of John]] was also attributed.<ref name=\"ODCC Revelation, Book of\"/> The early-2nd-century writer, [[Justin Martyr]], was the first to equate the author of Revelation with [[John the Evangelist]].<ref name=\"Justin\">Justin Martyr, ''Dialogue with Trypho'', 81.4</ref> Other early Christian writers, however, such as [[Dionysius of Alexandria]] and [[Eusebius of Caesarea]], noting the  differences in language and theological outlook between this work and the Gospel,<ref>Ben Witherington, ''Revelation'', (Cambridge University Press) page 2.</ref> discounted this possibility, and argued for the exclusion of the Book of Revelation from the canon as a result.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ehrman |first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |title=The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=0-19-515462-2 |page=432 }}</ref> The early Christian writer [[Papias of Hierapolis|Papias]] appeared in his writings to distinguish between [[John the Evangelist]] and [[John the Elder]],<ref>Richard Bauckham, ''Jesus and the Eyewitnesses'' (William B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2006)</ref> and many biblical scholars now contend that the latter was the author of Revelation.<ref>Robert H. Mounce, ''The Book of Revelation'' (Wm B. Eerdmans Publications) page 10.</ref><ref>[[Stephen L Harris|Harris, Stephen L.]], ''Understanding the Bible''. Palo Alto: Mayfield. 1985. p. 355</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Ehrman |first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |title=''The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings'' |year=2004 |publisher=Oxford |location=New York |isbn=0-19-515462-2 |page=468 }}</ref>\n\n== Island of Patmos ==\nJohn is considered to have been exiled to [[Patmos]] during a time of persecution under the Roman rule of [[Domitian]] in the late 1st century. {{Bibleref2|Revelation |1:9}} states: \"I, John, both your brother and companion in tribulation...was on the island that is called Patmos for the word of God and for the testimony of Jesus Christ.\" [[Adela Yarbro Collins]], a biblical scholar at [[Yale Divinity School]], writes:\n<blockquote>Early tradition says that John was banished to Patmos by the Roman authorities. This tradition is credible because banishment was a common punishment used during the Imperial period for a number of offenses. Among such offenses were the practices of magic and astrology. Prophecy was viewed by the Romans as belonging to the same category, whether Pagan, Jewish, or Christian. Prophecy with political implications, like that expressed by John in the Book of Revelation, would have been perceived as a threat to Roman political power and order. Three of the islands in the [[Sporades]] were places where political offenders were banished. (Pliny, ''Natural History'' 4.69&ndash;70; Tacitus, ''Annals'' 4.30)<ref>Adela Collins. (1985). \"Patmos\" [In] Paul J. Achtemeier [Ed.]. (1985) ''Harper's Bible Dictionary''. San Francisco, CA: Harper & Row. p.&nbsp;755.</ref></blockquote>\n\nAccording to [[Tertullian]] (in ''The Prescription of Heretics'') John was banished after being plunged into boiling oil in Rome and suffering nothing from it. It is said that all in the audience of the Colosseum were converted to Christianity upon witnessing this miracle.{{citation needed|date= April 2020}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Authorship of the Johannine works]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Wikiquote-inline}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{Apostles}}\n{{Book of Revelation}}\n{{New Testament people|prophets|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John Of Patmos}}\n[[Category:1st-century apocalypticists]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christians]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:1st-century writers]]\n[[Category:2nd-century Christians]]\n[[Category:Angelic visionaries]]\n[[Category:Book of Revelation]]\n[[Category:Christian saints from the New Testament]]\n[[Category:Christian writers about eschatology]]\n[[Category:Jewish Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:John the Apostle]]\n[[Category:Patmos]]\n[[Category:People from Patmos]]\n[[Category:Prophets of the New Testament]]\n[[Category:Saints from the Holy Land]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Christian saint and author of the Book of Revelation}}\n{{Redirect2|John the Divine|John the Revelator|other uses of John the Divine|John the Divine (disambiguation)|other uses of John the Revelator|John the Revelator (disambiguation)|other people called Saint John|Saint John (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox saint\n|name=John of Patmos\n|birth_date=6 AD\n|death_date=~100 AD\n|feast_day=\n|venerated_in= [[Catholic Church]]<br/>[[Eastern Orthodox Church]] \n|image=File:Antonio Palomino 003.JPG\n|imagesize=250px\n|caption=''Saint John the Evangelist on Patmos'' by [[Antonio Palomino]], 17th century\n|death_place=[[Ephesus]], [[Roman Empire]] (?)\n|birth_place= [[Pool of Bethesda]], [[Jerusalem]]\n|beatified_date=\n|beatified_place=\n|beatified_by=\n|canonized_date=\n|major_works=[[Book of Revelation]]\n|canonized_by=\n|attributes=\n|patronage=\n|major_shrine=\n|suppressed_date=\n|issues=\n|prayer=\n|prayer_attrib=\n}}\n{{John}}\n'''John of Patmos''' (also called '''John the Revelator''', '''John the Divine''', '''John the Theologian''', and possibly [[John the Apostle]]; [[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: \u1f38\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u1f41 \u0398\u03b5\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2; {{lang-cop|\u2c93\u2cb1\u2c81\u2c9b\u2c9b\u2c8f\u2ca5}}) could be the author named as John in the [[Book of Revelation]], the [[Apocalyptic literature|apocalyptic]] text forming the final book of the [[New Testament]]. The text of Revelation states that John was on [[Patmos]], a [[Greece|Greek]] island where, by most biblical historians, he is considered to be exiled as a result of anti-Christian persecution under the Roman emperor [[Domitian]].<ref>Souvay, Charles. [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11547a.htm \"Patmos.\"] ''The Catholic Encyclopedia.'' Vol. 11. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 12 Jan. 2009</ref><ref>Phillips, J. B. {{cite web |url=http://www.ccel.org/bible/phillips/CPn27Revelation.htm |title= Book 27 - Book of Revelation |author= |date=12 January 1962 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=}} ''People, Places, Customs, Concepts, Journeys - the New Testament with integrated notes and maps 1962.</ref> \n\nSince the Roman era, Christians and historians have considered the Book of Revelation's writer to be the Apostle John (John the Evangelist), author of the [[Gospel of John]]. However, a minority of senior clerics and scholars, such as [[Eusebius]] (d. 339/340), recognize at least one further John as a companion of Jesus Christ, [[John the Presbyter]] \"after an interval, placing him among others outside of the number of the apostles\". Some Christian scholars since medieval times separate the disciple(s) from Revelation's writer, John of Patmos/the Divine.<ref name=Harris>Stephen L Harris, ''Understanding the Bible,'' (Palo Alto: Mayfield, 1985), 355</ref><ref name=Ehrman>{{Cite book|last=Ehrman |first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |title=The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings |year=2004 |publisher=Oxford |location=New York |isbn=0-19-515462-2 |page=468 }}</ref>\n\n== Book of Revelation ==\nThe author of the [[Book of Revelation]] identifies himself only as \"John\".<ref name=\"ODCC Revelation, Book of\">\"Revelation, Book of.\" Cross, F. L., ed. The Oxford dictionary of the Christian church. New York: Oxford University Press. 2005</ref> Traditionally, this was often believed to be the same person as [[John the Apostle|John, son of Zebedee]], one of the apostles of Jesus, to whom the [[Gospel of John]] was also attributed.<ref name=\"ODCC Revelation, Book of\"/> The early-2nd-century writer, [[Justin Martyr]], was the first to equate the author of Revelation with [[John the Evangelist]].<ref name=\"Justin\">Justin Martyr, ''Dialogue with Trypho'', 81.4</ref> Other early Christian writers, however, such as [[Dionysius of Alexandria]] and [[Eusebius of Caesarea]], noting the  differences in language and theological outlook between this work and the Gospel,<ref>Ben Witherington, ''Revelation'', (Cambridge University Press) page 2.</ref> discounted this possibility, and argued for the exclusion of the Book of Revelation from the canon as a result.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ehrman |first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |title=The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=0-19-515462-2 |page=432 }}</ref> The early Christian writer [[Papias of Hierapolis|Papias]] appeared in his writings to distinguish between [[John the Evangelist]] and [[John the Elder]],<ref>Richard Bauckham, ''Jesus and the Eyewitnesses'' (William B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2006)</ref> and many biblical scholars now contend that the latter was the author of Revelation.<ref>Robert H. Mounce, ''The Book of Revelation'' (Wm B. Eerdmans Publications) page 10.</ref><ref>[[Stephen L Harris|Harris, Stephen L.]], ''Understanding the Bible''. Palo Alto: Mayfield. 1985. p. 355</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Ehrman |first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |title=''The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings'' |year=2004 |publisher=Oxford |location=New York |isbn=0-19-515462-2 |page=468 }}</ref>\n\n== Island of Patmos ==\nJohn is considered to have been exiled to [[Patmos]] during a time of persecution under the Roman rule of [[Domitian]] in the late 1st century. {{Bibleref2|Revelation |1:9}} states: \"I, John, both your brother and companion in tribulation...was on the island that is called Patmos for the word of God and for the testimony of Jesus Christ.\" [[Adela Yarbro Collins]], a biblical scholar at [[Yale Divinity School]], writes:\n<blockquote>Early tradition says that John was banished to Patmos by the Roman authorities. This tradition is credible because banishment was a common punishment used during the Imperial period for a number of offenses. Among such offenses were the practices of magic and astrology. Prophecy was viewed by the Romans as belonging to the same category, whether Pagan, Jewish, or Christian. Prophecy with political implications, like that expressed by John in the Book of Revelation, would have been perceived as a threat to Roman political power and order. Three of the islands in the [[Sporades]] were places where political offenders were banished. (Pliny, ''Natural History'' 4.69&ndash;70; Tacitus, ''Annals'' 4.30)<ref>Adela Collins. (1985). \"Patmos\" [In] Paul J. Achtemeier [Ed.]. (1985) ''Harper's Bible Dictionary''. San Francisco, CA: Harper & Row. p.&nbsp;755.</ref></blockquote>\n\nAccording to [[Tertullian]] (in ''The Prescription of Heretics'') John was banished after being plunged into boiling oil in Rome and suffering nothing from it. It is said that all in the audience of the Colosseum were converted to Christianity upon witnessing this miracle.{{citation needed|date= April 2020}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Authorship of the Johannine works]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Wikiquote-inline}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{Apostles}}\n{{Book of Revelation}}\n{{New Testament people|prophets|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John Of Patmos}}\n[[Category:1st-century apocalypticists]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christians]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:1st-century writers]]\n[[Category:2nd-century Christians]]\n[[Category:Angelic visionaries]]\n[[Category:Book of Revelation]]\n[[Category:Christian saints from the New Testament]]\n[[Category:Christian writers about eschatology]]\n[[Category:Jewish Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:John the Apostle]]\n[[Category:Patmos]]\n[[Category:People from Patmos]]\n[[Category:Prophets of the New Testament]]\n[[Category:Saints from the Holy Land]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "name_user": "Endlesspumpkin", "label": "safe", "comment": "turned 'John the Evangelist' into a link to that page.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_of_Patmos"}
